The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Oriental sees drop in profit
                                                                                                               Oriental sees drop in profit
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                              
	New Delhi, April 17: Public sector Oriental Insurance Company expects a profit decline of around Rs 300 crore in 2008-09 because of the downturn.        
	We registered a profit of Rs 453 crore in fiscal 2007-08, but it is expected to take a hit of around Rs 300 crore over last year. So, we are looking at a profit before tax of Rs 100-150 crore, said M. Ramadoss, chairman and managing director of Oriental Insurance.        
	We expect underwriting losses to be more and also investment income to take a hit, but I cant assign a figure right now, he said.        
	Premium growth was likely to remain flat in 2009-10 at around 7-8 per cent. The insurer is expected to report lower premium growth of around 7 per cent in 2008-09 at Rs 4,075 crore against Rs 3,800 crore in 2007-08. The companys motor insurance is also expected to remain flat for most part of this fiscal.                                                                                                                                        
